                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17721209-33-victim346 t17721209-33-viclabel180"></join>. The prisoner and another came to my house this day sevennight, about ten at night; after they had drank something, they wanted change for a 5 s. and 3 d. I weighed it, and thought it not good; I did not change it; they drank their liquor, and went away, but left a small bundle behind them; they returned for it in about half an hour, and then the prisoner ordered a pint of beer; he desired me to give him<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177212090017"></xptr> a half crown piece for 2 s. and 6 d. he pretended he had wrote a letter to his sister, in which he had informed her he had inclosed a half crown piece; I took out a handful of silver, looked it over, and found I had no half crown; then he desired to have a Queen-Ann's shilling or two; I drew my money over my hand to see if I had any of that coin; the prisoner put three fingers and his thumb among the money, and said I think that further one is a Queen-Ann's shilling; he took seven or eight shillings in his hand; he turned them over, and said there is no Queen-Ann's shilling here, and returned 4 s. into my hand; I was confident he kept back some; I was determined to detect him; I thought if I did not mention any thing he might make another dip: I observed him put his hand to his pocket; I 
               <persName id="t17721209-33-person348">
                  drew
               <interp inst="t17721209-33-person348" type="given" value="drew"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17721209-33-person348" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             the money over my hand again, and separated 6 s. which I put towards the tip of my finger: the prisoner said sure there must be one Queen-Ann's shilling among all this number; he took the six up and looked them over and said no, there is none, and he threw back 3 s. then he gave me 6 d. and seemed to be in a hurry, I told him I was in no hurry; I desired to see what he had in his hand; he opened his hand, and under his thumb I found 3 s. the lad that came with him stood by, with a canvas bag in his hand; in the hurry he got away; I took the prisoner into a parlour; he said he would return my money if I would let him go; he said he had never been guilty of it before; that the other had learnt him the trick that night.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence.</p>
               <p>I took none of his money; I was rather in liquor.</p>
               <p>He called two witnesses who gave him a very good character.</p>
